    <text>
        <body>
            <div frus:doc-dateTime-max="1953-04-11T07:00:00-05:00"
                frus:doc-dateTime-min="1953-04-11T07:00:00-05:00" n="859"
                subtype="historical-document" type="document" xml:id="d859">
                <note rend="inline" type="source">763.00/4–1153: Telegram</note>
                <head>No. 859<lb/>
                    <hi rend="italic">The United States High Commissioner for Austria (<persName
                            corresp="#p_TLE1" type="from">Thompson</persName>) to the <gloss
                            type="to">Department of State</gloss>
                    </hi>
                </head>
                <opener>
                    <seg rendition="#left">
                        <hi rend="smallcaps">secret</hi>
                    </seg>
                    <dateline rendition="#right">
                        <placeName>
                            <hi rend="smallcaps">Vienna</hi>
                        </placeName>, <date calendar="gregorian" when="1953-04-11T13:00:00+01:00"
                            >April 11, 1953—1 p.m.</date>
                    </dateline>
                </opener>
                <p>2926. In discussions with Chancellor <persName corresp="#p_RJ1">Raab</persName>
                    <note n="1" xml:id="d859fn1">Following weeks of negotiations between the
                        People’s Party and the Socialist Party, agreement was reached on Apr. 1
                        concerning the formation of a coalition government under <persName
                            corresp="#p_RJ1">Julius Raab</persName>, who replaced <persName
                            corresp="#p_FL1">Leopold Figl</persName> as Austrian Chancellor. The new
                        government was sworn in on Apr. 2.</note> on April 9 and 10 following
                    questions were discussed in general terms: <list>
                        <label>(1)</label>
                        <item>State treaty. <persName corresp="#p_RJ1">Raab</persName> indicated
                            Cabinet decision on withdrawal of abbreviated draft was less firm than
                                <persName corresp="#p_GK1">Gruber</persName> had led us to believe.
                            I explained to him yesterday (prior receipt <gloss target="#t_Deptel1"
                                >Deptel</gloss> 2978<note n="2" xml:id="d859fn2">Telegram 2978
                                recommended an early move on the Austrian Treaty and the convening
                                of a new meeting of the Austrian Treaty Deputies.
                                (663.001/4–1053)</note> reasons why we were reluctant withdraw
                            abbreviated draft, emphasizing that our objective was an Austria
                            independent both politically and economically.</item>
                        <label>(2)</label>
                        <item>Restitution. I said I gathered from press that his government wished
                            to take some steps for further rehabilitation of former Nazis. I
                            explained our position that victims should come first and urged that
                            they quickly institute negotiations with representatives Jewish
                            organizations and pass further legislation to assist victims. <persName
                                corresp="#p_RJ1">Raab</persName> said Cabinet on Thursday had set up
                            committee of three to be headed by <persName corresp="#p_KR1"
                                >Kamitz</persName> to negotiation with Jewish
                            representatives.</item>
                        <label>(3)</label>
                        <item>Economic situation. I expressed concern at Austria’s weak competitive
                            position and urged that prompt steps be taken to balance budget, remove
                            restrictions on competition and overcome obstacles to productivity
                            drive. <persName corresp="#p_RJ1">Raab</persName> said Cabinet would
                            next week firm up budget which would be virtual prolongation of 1952
                            budget but with clear understanding that Finance Minister had power to
                                <pb facs="0649" n="1849" xml:id="pg_1849"/> limit expenditures to
                            receipts. He expressed sympathy with objectives of productivity drive
                            and suggested we should all do more to convince labor of its
                            necessity.</item>
                        <label>(4)</label>
                        <item>Bank investigation. <persName corresp="#p_RJ1">Raab</persName> said
                            his party had become convinced that we were right in advocating
                            termination control of nationalized banks over Austrian industry and
                            while there were many difficulties they would endeavor to accomplish
                            this. Indicated they were motivated by fear Socialists might come to
                            power and spread nationalization of industry through control of
                            banks.</item>
                        <label>(5)</label>
                        <item>Revision Nazi laws. <persName corresp="#p_RJ1">Raab</persName>
                            promised action on this long-standing question which has embarrassed us
                            in <gloss target="#t_AC1">AC</gloss> and could be used by Russians in
                            treaty negotiations to demonstrate Austrian lack of interest in
                            denazification.</item>
                    </list>
                </p>
                <p>
                    <persName corresp="#p_RJ1">Raab</persName> expressed gratitude for US assistance
                    and said we could count upon Austria to continue fight against communism.</p>
                <closer>
                    <signed>
                        <persName corresp="#p_TLE1">
                            <hi rend="smallcaps">Thompson</hi>
                        </persName>
                    </signed>
                </closer>
            </div>
        </body>
